=== Ch2_Q24 ===
Questions 24-26 ask about "persuasive" design features:

"Which of the following do you think are particularly persuasive to children?"

The list: Infinite scrolling. Autoplay. Likes and comments. Push notifications. Content recommendation algorithms.

*   [These do seem problematic though?]
    -> Ch2_Q24_Analysis

=== Ch2_Q24_Analysis ===
They can be. But the question describes them as features that "encourage children to stay online longer"—and they're the fundamental architecture of the modern internet.

Recommendation algorithms power YouTube educational content as much as they power harmful content. The question doesn't distinguish between "all algorithmic recommendation" and "harmful algorithmic recommendation."

Removing algorithms doesn't remove content—it just makes feeds chronological, which can actually be worse. You see everything, unfiltered, in order of posting rather than relevance. The algorithm that shows a child their friend's art project is the same one that might show harmful content—the problem is the content policies, not the mechanism.

*   [What about screen time limits?]
    -> Ch2_Q27

=== Ch2_Q27 ===
Question 27 asks:

"Would you support daily screen time limits for individual apps? Restricting overnight access? Both? Neither?"

*   [Isn't this reasonable?]
    -> Ch2_Q27_Analysis

=== Ch2_Q27_Analysis ===
On the surface, yes. But consider: who enforces app-level time limits?

On-device parental controls already do this. Apple's Screen Time, Google's Family Link—parents can set these today, per app, per child, no government involvement needed.

The question is really asking: should the government mandate that platforms enforce time limits server-side? That means platforms need to know each user's age, track their usage across sessions, and cut them off. More surveillance, more data collection, more age verification.

If you already have parental controls that do this better—locally, without sending data to anyone—why build a government-mandated alternative that requires surveillance infrastructure?

If this is your view, say so. The free-text box in Q28 is where you make the case for on-device controls over server-side mandates.

